National NHS-R Community Conference, 11th November 2020

Introduction

  • British Medical Journal (BMJ) publishes obituaries on medical figures who have recently died
  • Written in prose, but always containing same variables

  • name, dob, date of death, cause of death, specialty, number of children, qualifying university, professional affiliations.

  • Aim: automate the extraction of meaningful data from free text on a publically available website?

Methodology - Sample webpage

Methodology - Sample webpage

Previous work

  • Wright et. al (1996) used a sample of 572 obituaries, finding that doctors born in the Indian subcontinent die earlier than those born in the United Kingdom.
  • Patel et al. (2009) used 3342 obituaries to describe that primary care doctors can expect to live 20 years longer than an emergency medicine doctor.

Methodology - What is web-scraping

Getting data off a website in a systematic way, can involve:

  • Copy-Paste
  • HTML Parsing: using HTML structure "tags" to pull out target
  • API

Results

  • 8156 obituaries accessed between 1997-2019
  • 84.5% male
  • average age at death 79 years
  • Lowest age at death 58.7 (emergency medicine), oldest 80.3 (primary care)
  • Just 3.4% of all surgeons were women
  • Cancer was a more common cause of death (39%) than heart and circulatory (27%, bucks trend for UK population)

Results - Relative survival analysis

library(relsurv)

Limitations

Key points

  • There is lots of quality data online
  • Web scraping is easy and can make these data accessible
  • Automated analysis is extremely accurate for simple variables, but performs worse with more complex variables
  • Machine learning could improve on this performance
  • Our study presents the largest ever analysis of medical obituary data
